#############Phase 1 - Scope Lock (Day 1-2)

Define objective: binary classification (Normal vs Pneumonia) and freeze scope to one dataset only.

Lock success metrics: F1, Recall (Sensitivity), Precision, ROC-AUC, confusion matrix.

Lock communication rule: educational/research project only, explicitly not for clinical diagnosis.

Output: one-page project brief (goal, data, metrics, risks).

############Phase 2 - Data and Experiment Design (Week 1)

Select Kaggle chest X-ray dataset and document data provenance, class distribution, and known limitations.

Predefine split policy: train/validation/test with stratification; patient-level split when metadata allows to prevent leakage.

Predefine imbalance strategy: class weights or weighted sampling (pick one and keep it consistent).

Output: experiment protocol document finalized before model training.

#############Phase 3 - Baseline First (Week 2)

Build baseline model track using a standard CNN transfer-learning setup (this is the benchmark anchor).

Record full metric panel on validation set and capture training behavior notes (stability, overfitting signs).

Output: baseline results table + confusion matrix + short observations.

#############Phase 4 - ViT Improved Track (Week 3)

Train ViT as the second model (not replacement for baseline), using same split and same evaluation protocol.

Keep comparison fair: identical dataset, no test-set tuning, same reporting template.

Document compute/training trade-offs (time, resource usage, augmentation sensitivity).

Output: side-by-side baseline vs ViT comparison sheet.

##############Phase 5 - Final Evaluation and Error Analysis (Week 4)

Run one-time final test evaluation after model choices are fixed.

Perform error analysis focused on false negatives, low-quality images, and class-confusion patterns.

Write limitations section: dataset bias, domain shift risk, no external clinical validation.

Output: final results report with decision rationale for best model.

#############Phase 6 - Portfolio Packaging (Week 4-5, parallel after Phase 3 stabilizes)

Prepare GitHub-ready narrative structure: problem, data, method, metrics, errors, limitations, reproducibility steps.

Prepare Kaggle evidence: EDA + baseline/improved result story.

Prepare Hugging Face publishing plan: model card with intended use, metrics, and safety limitations.

Output: recruiter-facing artifact checklist completed.

#############Phase 7 - Application Conversion (Week 5-6)

Create resume bullet set from measured outcomes only (no inflated claims).

Create LinkedIn summary with one insight from error analysis and one model-comparison insight.

Define interview story: what failed first, what changed, and why final model was chosen.

Output: job-application-ready talking points tied to your project evidence.

Dependencies and Parallelism

Phases 1-2 must complete before any model work.
Phase 3 blocks Phase 4 (ViT requires baseline reference).
Phase 5 depends on Phases 3-4 being frozen.
Phase 6 can begin after Phase 3 and run parallel with Phase 4-5 documentation updates.
Phase 7 depends on Phase 5 results being finalized.
Verification

Scope verification: confirm project remains binary classification with one dataset and no scope creep.
Protocol verification: confirm leakage control, split strategy, and imbalance handling are written before training.
Fair-comparison verification: confirm CNN baseline and ViT use identical split/evaluation criteria.
Reporting verification: confirm final report includes non-accuracy metrics and error analysis.
Safety verification: confirm all public text includes non-clinical-use disclaimer.
Portfolio verification: confirm three visible artifacts exist in plan (Kaggle evidence, GitHub project narrative, Hugging Face model card/demo plan).
Decisions

Included: planning only; no coding.
Included: Kaggle-first execution and Hugging Face publication strategy.
Included: ViT as improved-model track after a CNN baseline.
Excluded: multi-class disease detection, advanced ensembling, clinical-grade claims.
Further Considerations

Final model rule: pick the model with better Recall and F1 on test set unless compute cost is much higher for very small gains.
If ViT gain is small, use CNN as your main final story and present ViT as a controlled comparison experiment.
After this flagship project, add one non-medical analytics project to widen your Werkstudent role fit.
